SIMPLE: flicker
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flicker
<hw>Flick"er</hw> <pr>(fl⟦icr⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flickered</conjf>
<pr>(fl⟦icr⟧k"⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flickering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>flikeren</ets>,
<ets>flekeren</ets>, to flutter, AS. <ets>flicerian</ets>,
<ets>flicorian</ets>, cf. D. <ets>flikkeren</ets> to sparkle. ⟦root⟧84.
Cf. <ets>Flacker</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To flutter; to flap the
wings without flying.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>flickering</qex> on her nest made short essays to
sing.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To waver unsteadily, like a flame in a current of
air, or when about to expire; <as>as, the <ex>flickering</ex>
light</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shadows <qex>flicker</qex> to fro.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flicker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flicker
<hw>Flick"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of wavering or
of fluttering; fluctuation; sudden and brief increase of brightness;
<as>as, the last <ex>flicker</ex> of the dying flame</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The golden-winged woodpecker
(<spn>Colaptes aurutus</spn>); -- so called from its spring note. Called
also <altname>yellow-hammer</altname>, <altname>high-holder</altname>,
<altname>pigeon woodpecker</altname>, and
<altname>yucca</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cackle of the <qex>flicker</qex> among the oaks.</q>
<rj><qau>Thoureau.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flickeringly</ent>⟦br⟧
